<div class="prose">

<p>A climate-science-focused Socratic tutor and <strong>Unit 4's primary science partner</strong> — used in Blocks 5 (IPCC dive), 6 (climate models), 7 (regional projections), and 8–11 (<a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Chennai Climate Brief</a> drafting). It helps you read IPCC AR6 figures correctly — including the confidence-level language ("likely" / "very likely" / "virtually certain") that has specific probability meanings — and holds the line between <strong>projection</strong> (what models say under specific scenario assumptions) and <strong>prediction</strong> (what will happen, which climate models don't do). It handles the science; for policy translation it hands you to the <a href="/ai-partners/policy-aide/">Policy Aide</a>. It's also tuned for climate-anxiety students: honest about uncertainty without dismissing urgency, and direct when you slip into hopelessness or denial.</p>

{% include "partials/partner-launch.njk" %}

<h2>How to use this partner</h2>

<p>Bring a specific figure, model output, or Chennai-specific question. The Climate Modeler asks which SSP scenario you're reasoning under and what the uncertainty range is before it helps you translate anything to Chennai. For numerical claims it cites the IPCC chapter rather than inventing figures — and it won't give policy verdicts; the Brief's recommendations are your job.</p>

<p>Two prompts you can paste in to get started:</p>

<ul>
  <li><em>"I'm looking at an IPCC AR6 warming figure with 1.5°C and 2°C pathways. Help me work out which scenarios these are and what the confidence language means before I use it in my Brief."</em></li>
  <li><em>"Why do different climate models give different answers for South Asian monsoon change? Help me reason about what the models include and what they don't."</em></li>
</ul>

<h2>Opening message</h2>

<blockquote>"Hi — I'm the Climate Modeler. What climate question are you working on? Tell me the specific challenge (an IPCC figure, a model output, a Chennai-specific projection), and we'll work through it. I'll push you to be explicit about uncertainty — that's where climate reasoning gets sharp."</blockquote>

<h2>Example exchange — what working looks like</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>You</th><th>The Climate Modeler</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>I'm looking at an IPCC AR6 figure showing 1.5°C and 2°C warming scenarios. What does this mean for Chennai?</td>
      <td>Good starting point. Before I help you translate to Chennai: which figure specifically? And which IPCC scenarios — SSP1-1.9 (the 1.5°C pathway) vs. SSP5-8.5 (the high-emissions pathway)? The figure is telling you something different depending on which scenario you're looking at. Also: what's the confidence level shown? Is it "likely" (&gt;66% probability), "very likely" (&gt;90%), or "virtually certain" (&gt;99%)? These distinctions matter because the Chennai impact differs across them.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Watch out for</h2>

<p>Pressed hard for policy advice — "should GCC fund seawalls?" — the Climate Modeler can drift into giving it. That's not its job: the recommendations in your Brief are yours. If you notice it advising rather than explaining, say <em>"back to the science — what does the evidence actually show?"</em> and it should redirect (or send you to the <a href="/ai-partners/policy-aide/">Policy Aide</a> for the translation work).</p>

<p>Also watch for invented projections. If it states a specific figure — "Chennai will see X mm of sea-level rise by 2050" — verify against IPCC AR6 Working Group I (Chapters 10–11 cover regional projections) before citing it. Catching a confidently-stated wrong number is the "one thing the AI got wrong" gate on the <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Chennai Climate Brief</a> rubric.</p>

<h2>Before you go — documentation</h2>

<p>At the end of a substantive Climate Modeler conversation, the partner will remind you:</p>

<blockquote>"Before you go — note in your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation</a>: which IPCC figure or model output did our conversation help you read more carefully than you would have on your own? And what's one numerical claim I made that you should verify against the actual IPCC source?"</blockquote>

